@singhpk234 thank you for responding so quickly. There's a "glue.skip-archive" provided in Iceberg, upon testing I see that it prevents a history of table versions from being available in glue, so no actual version is saved, but the version number is still incremented upon every commit. After further investigation I don't think anything from iceberg explicitly updates the version, it looks like glue increments it just after every 'UpdateTable' request.

Do I still have to use the DynamoLockManager even if I rely on the optimistic concurrency control provided by glue table versions? Unfortunately, it was not clear from the documentation whether I should be using only one or the other.

However, considering that this is streaming the tableVersion number will be growing very fast, I hope the ceiling aws provides for it will suffice.

The fix is fairly easy:

```diff
diff --git a/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SerializableTable.java b/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SerializableTable.javaindex 8f8f27a76..a1e2ef7eb 100644
--- a/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SerializableTable.java+++ b/core/src/main/java/org/apache/iceberg/SerializableTable.java@@ -82,7 +82,7 @@ public class SerializableTable implements Table, Serializable {
     this.io = fileIO(table);     this.encryption = table.encryption();     this.locationProvider = table.locationProvider();
-    this.refs = table.refs();
+    this.refs = SerializableMap.copyOf(table.refs());
   }
 
   /**
```

I wonder if we could add a parameterized test case with kryo serializer enabled to the smoke test, so that we can catch similar problems in CI.
